3. Implementation Plan (The "Fix")

To clean up this mess and lock the doors, we are taking the following steps:

    Eviction: Immediately delete the unauthorized accounts and revert the rogue firewall rules found during the audit.

    Patching: Upgrade the kernel and OS to the latest stable version to close the vulnerabilities found in our current setup.

    Credential Reset: Force a password reset for the compromised account and implement Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) across the board.

    Service Hardening: Restrict access to the entry-point service so it only accepts traffic from known, trusted IP addresses.

4. Monitoring Protocol (The "Safety Net")

We can't just fix it once; we have to keep watching. Our new monitoring strategy includes:

    Real-Time Alerts: We’ve set up automated triggers that ping the security team the moment a new user is created or a firewall rule is changed.

    Log Integrity: We are moving our logs to a remote, read-only server. This prevents attackers from deleting their history if they ever get back in.

    Weekly Audits: Every Friday, we will run the forensic scripts developed during this project to check for any "uniqueness" in login patterns or unauthorized IP spikes.
